explanation:
For deciding whether any part of OS_rename is dead code (i.e. can be removed without affecting program behaviour) you must understand every condition and side-effect in the function and every place that could observe the side-effect. The following explains why each symbol is required:

- OS_TranslatePath: determines whether the early-return behavior (skipping later code) can occur. Need its return semantics to know if the rename/loop code executes.

- OS_FileRename_Impl: the core filesystem rename operation. If this fails/succeeds affects whether the subsequent object-table update executes and therefore whether that update is necessary or dead.

- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive: establishes the object-iterator used to walk objects. Need to know whether it actually selects/limits objects (which affects whether the loop body ever runs).

- OS_object_iter_t: the iterator type and fields (e.g. token) are required to interpret iteration results and mapping to table entries.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: controls loop iteration. Its semantics (return values, side-effects) determine whether the while loop body can execute and how many entries are visited.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: may involve transaction cancel/cleanup that could interact with object visibility; required to understand lifetime/side-effects of the iteration.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro/function used to map iterator.token to a table entry. Need its definition to know how token indexes map to stream table and whether access is valid.

- OS_stream_table: the global table being modified. Must inspect it to know if updating stream_name affects observable behaviour elsewhere (i.e. whether writing into this table is meaningful or unused).

- OS_stream_internal_record_t: the structure definition (fields and types) is needed to know the meaning of socket_domain and stream_name, to find stream_name length and to reason about side-effects of modifying it.

- OS_SocketDomain_t / OS_SocketDomain_INVALID: the enum value tested in the if-condition; needed to determine when the stream-name update is applied (only for non-socket streams) and whether that condition can ever be true.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: the object-type identifier passed to the iterator; needed to determine which objects are iterated (streams vs other object kinds) and thus whether the loop will encounter stream records.

- OS_SUCCESS: return-code constant used throughout for flow control; needed to determine which branches execute and whether subsequent code is dead.

- OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN: buffer length used for old_path/new_path; necessary to check for truncation/overflow effects that could change control flow or observable behaviour.

- strcmp: used to compare stream->stream_name with the caller-supplied old; its semantics decide whether the conditional that updates the name can ever be true (and whether that check has side-effects).

- strncpy: used to update stream->stream_name; need its exact semantics (including NUL handling) to reason whether the write changes behaviour or is a no-op.

- stream->stream_name (size/definition): the exact array size and lifetime (inside OS_stream_internal_record_t) is required to know whether the strncpy call can actually modify content and whether that modification is observable.

- OS_OpenCreate: a likely writer/initializer of stream->stream_name. To decide if updating stream_name is dead you must know how/when it is set elsewhere; OS_OpenCreate (or similar open/create functions) is a primary candidate.

- OS_FileOpenCheck: a likely reader of stream->stream_name; needed to determine whether other code consults stream_name and thus whether changing it affects program behaviour.

- OS_CloseFileByName: another function that may search/compare stream names; required to see whether renaming stream_name is relied upon elsewhere.

- OS_CloseAllFiles: may iterate/operate on stream table; needed to see whether stream_name is observed and whether the update is necessary.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: often used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or by index->object translations; needed if OBJECT_TABLE_GET expands to or relies on this to ensure correct mapping and to reason about validity of the access.

Notes: The minimal set includes the iterator APIs, the stream table and its record type, the constants controlling flow, and the functions which set or read stream->stream_name. Without these symbols you cannot determine (a) whether the loop body ever executes, (b) whether the strncpy write can change observable program state, or (c) whether removing the rename-of-stream-name would be behaviour-preserving — which is required to assess the MISRA "no dead code" rule.
